        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B. Vitamin A excess</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Bulging of the anterior fontanelle </strong>in the <strong>absence of fever </strong>or <strong>signs of trauma </strong>or <strong>intracranial mass on CT scan</strong>, especially in an <strong>infant </strong>with a <strong>history of Cystic Fibrosis</strong>, raises the concern for <strong>vitamin A toxicity</strong>. <strong>Children with Cystic Fibrosis </strong>are often given <strong>vitamin supplements </strong>due to <strong>malabsorption issues </strong>associated with their condition, and <strong>excessive vitamin A </strong>can <strong>lead to increased intracranial pressure</strong>, presenting with symptoms such as <strong>bulging fontanelle, fussiness, and vomiting.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Colic</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Colic is characterized by <strong>periods of intense</strong>, <strong>unexplained fussiness </strong>and <strong>crying in an otherwise healthy infant</strong>, not typically associated with bulging fontanelle or vomiting.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Sinusitis</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: While <strong>recurrent respiratory infections </strong>are common in <strong>Cystic Fibrosis</strong>, sinusitis would not explain the bulging fontanelle and absence of fever.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Pneumonia</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Pneumonia could <strong>cause vomiting </strong>and <strong>fussiness </strong>but would generally <strong>present with fever and respiratory symptoms </strong>rather than bulging of the anterior fontanelle.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Malabsorption </strong>of <strong>fats and protein are major causes of morbidity </strong>for patients with <strong>Cystic Fibrosis</strong>. In addition to carefully <strong>planned diets</strong>, <strong>most children </strong>with <strong>CF take supplements </strong>of the <strong>fat-soluble vitamins D, E, K, and A</strong>. <strong>Disorders of vitamin A metabolism </strong>can result in <strong>pseudotumor cerebri </strong>(increased intracranial pressure), which cause <strong>headache</strong>, <strong>vomiting</strong>, and <strong>neurologic abnormalities</strong>. Thus, a bulging fontanelle may be the presenting sign of CF in an infant.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref: Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition &ndash;Chapter - 432 Page No-From 8205</span></span></strong></p>",
